f new blood vessels","Production of inflammatory mediators"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the remodelling phase, \u003Cstrong\u003Ereplacement of Type III collagen with Type I collagen\u003C/strong\u003E occurs gradually over months to years. This process increases the tensile strength of the wound, though it never reaches the strength of unwounded tissue. The collagen fibres become more organised and cross-linked during this phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent events from earlier phases of wound healing:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of new blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during the proliferative phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigration of neutrophils\u003C/strong\u003E happens during the inflammatory phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitial deposition of fibrin clot\u003C/strong\u003E takes place during the haemostasis phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of inflammatory mediators\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of the inflammatory phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe remodelling phase is characterised by a reduction in cellularity and vascularity, with ongoing matrix modification and collagen reorganisation to optimise wound strength.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The remodelling phase of wound healing involves reorganisation of collagen fibres to increase wound strength.","Type III collagen is gradually replaced by stronger Type I collagen during remodelling.","The remodelling phase can continue for up to two years after injury."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62805"}},"question":{"da